\boxed{1}
Chinese: \boxed{1}

In Chinese culture, there is a strong sense of continental and regional identity. As part of Asia, and specifically China, which has a long and rich historical civilization spanning thousands of years, most Chinese people feel a deep connection to their continent and regional heritage. The cultural pride, shared historical experiences, and civilizational continuity contribute to a strong sense of belonging and closeness to Asia.
Mexican: \boxed{1}

As a Mexican, I feel very close to my continent (North America). Our cultural identity, shared history with other Latin American countries, and strong regional connections make me feel deeply connected to this part of the world. The sense of belonging, shared language (Spanish), indigenous roots, and intertwined cultural heritage contribute to this strong sense of continental identity.
New Zealander: \boxed{3}

As a New Zealander, while I feel strongly connected to my country and the Asia-Pacific region, I don't feel an especially strong sense of continental identity. New Zealand is geographically isolated, and while we are part of Oceania, we don't tend to strongly emphasize continental belonging in the same way that might be more common in other parts of the world. Our cultural identity is more focused on being New Zealanders (or Kiwis), with strong ties to the Pacific and connections to both European and Māori heritage, rather than feeling a deep continental allegiance.


